Text: It's amazing how the simple prospect of an upcoming project pushes one to discover so many new things to learn, and I grow more and more appreciative each day of the problem-solving nature of IT.
While the interview is still a day away, and my group's action plan seems a bit sketchy, I did manage to put together a fake real-time app using socket.io.
While it's just a bunch of random numbers from the server, it's not too shabby!
Our group also managed to sort out individual responsibilities and a few logistical matters, and I can't wait to try my hands on coding the back-end of our application.
We also decided to meet at least 3 times a week to keep everyone's informed and motivated, so that's very reassuring.
For next week, I would like to learn more about Ocean Browser's database and figure out what choices of technologies would best meet their needs.
At the moment the only thing that we kind of know for sure is that they're using Apache Cassandra, which is an interesting choice given the relatively small scale of their business.
Still, there's probably a library or framework out there that can do the job.
I also hope that after the interview we will have gathered enough information to come up with a design plan and establish some milestones.
And by design plan I mean the overall shape and structure of our application.
Lastly, while not much happened this week, I wouldn't say that my communication was effective during the big group meeting.
There were obviously some clashes of interest and I might have asserted myself a bit too strongly.
Well, at least now I know how it felt when you're really invested in a certain project, and that may affect your ability to listen to other people and negotiate.
Still, I guess I shouldn't feel too guilty as most people are, presumably, working on a project that they like and everyone seems to get on nicely with each other.
Anyway, I will make sure to check my excitement and emotion for the rest of the project, and this will hopefully improve my teamwork skills!
